caption:
Explore V3 is an all-weather CE certified mesh riding jacket from Royal Enfield. The one I have is a full black colour one - my personal favourite. Compared to the Explore V2 version, the new upgrade has better protection with Knox MICRO-LOCK CE Level 2 protectors at elbow and shoulder and the jacket itself is CE certified. The jacket comes with a thermal liner and a rain jacket that can be worn as an inner or outer liner. The rain jacket fits in the back pocket of the jacket and so easily usable when it rains all suddenly. Fit of the jacket is also excellent and itâ€™s very light. The only thing that I feel could have been better is the back protector - it feels quiet thin. Apart from that, Explore V3 is good for daily use and long distance rides.

caption:
#BJsWholesalePartner Fall meals are my favorite to create, thereâ€™s just something about the 
warmth of cozy foods that brings me comfort. I want to share a yummy meal with you all, as a 
busy mom of 4 I want to make easy meals. Thanks to @BJsWholesale I can get everything I need 
in-club, online or even for pickup in-club. I was able to create this Chili-Bean Casserole just by 
going on the BJâ€™s app, ordering my ingredients and picking it up at a time convenient for my 
family and me. Be sure to go to my stories or click the link in my bio to shop and get the recipe 
card! #BJsSmartSaver #BJsWholesaleClub
Servings: 8 People 
Prep Time: 10 mins
Cook Time: 45 mins
Total Time: 55 mins 
1lb of Wellsley Farms Ground Beef 
2 8oz. cans tomato sauce

1 15oz. can kidney beans
1 15oz. can of corn
1 1.25oz. packet of chili seasoning
1 cup water
Cornbread Ingredients:
1/2 cup all-purpose flour
2 tbsp. Of Wellsley Farms Organic Cane Sugar
3/4 cup finely ground cornmeal
1/2 tsp. salt
1/2 tsp. baking soda
2/3 cup buttermilk
1/4 cup Wellsley Farms Canola Oil
1 Wellsley Farms egg
Toppings: (optional)
Wellsley Farms Mexican Shredded Cheese
Wellsley Farms Sour Cream

Preheat oven to 400 degrees Fahrenheit. To start making the cornbread layer, mix all the cornbread ingredients into a medium mixing bowl and mix until smooth. Pour into an 8in pan and bake for 12-16 mins or until light brown. 
While cornbread is baking put the kidney beans and corn on medium heat. In a separate pan
brown hamburger meat. Once meat is brown, add chili powder, water, tomato sauce and 
simmer for 10 mins. Drain kidney beans and corn, add it to the hamburger meat, and mix 
everything together. Put the beans, hamburger and corn mixture on top of the cornbread, add cheese (optional) and bake another 5-10 mins or until cheese is melted. Once itâ€™s had time to cool down cut and serve, please allow 10-15 mins to cool so that the cornbread has enough time to settle and not break apart.

caption:
When it gets cold out all I want to do is bake. I have loved baking for as long as I can remember. What is your favorite thing to bake? Thanks to @zulay_kitchen for #gifting me a 5 piece spatula set to make scraping down bowls and mixing a breeze. The spatulas  are silicon on the outside but have a sturdy stainless steel core. Use code happilyheatherj10 to save 10% on all your kitchen gaget needs. I included the recipe below for my oatmeal cookies 

1Â cupsÂ all-purpose flour

2 teaspoons Â cinnamonÂ to taste

1/2Â teaspoonÂ baking soda

1/4Â teaspoonÂ salt

1/2Â cupÂ unsalted butterÂ softened to room temperature

1/2Â cupÂ packed brown sugar

1/4Â cupÂ granulated sugar

1Â largeÂ egg

1Â tablespoonÂ honey

2Â teaspoonsÂ vanilla

1 and 1/2Â cupsÂ oatmealÂ 

2/3Â cupÂ raisins

Instructions

In a medium bowl, whisk together the flour, cinnamon, nutmeg, baking soda and salt.

In a large bowl using an electric mixer, beat together the butter, brown sugar and white sugar until fluffy (about 2 minutes).

Beat in the honey, vanilla extract and egg.

With the mixer on low speed, beat the flour mixture into the butter mixture.

Mix in the oats, followed by the raisins. The dough will be sticky.

Cover the bowl with plastic wrap, and refrigerate for 30 minutes or overnight.

When ready to bake, preheat the oven to 350F degrees. Line 2 cookie sheets with parchment paper.

Using a cookie scoop or tablespoon, form the dough into balls of about 1 to 2 tablespoons and place 2 inches apart on the lined cookie sheets.

Bake 1 tray at a time, on the middle rack of the oven for 9-11 minutes or until the tops look just set. 

Remove from the oven and cool fully on the cookie tray.

caption:
I'm not a crafty person at all but @solawoodflowers makes it easy. They have over 50 different flowers and dyed to choose from to make any flower craft imaginable. It was super easy to dye the flowers and actually really fun. Their website is filled with a ton of ideas to choose from. I wanted a cute centerpiece for my table and they had every color you can imagine. I also hand dyed some natural flowers to use as accents around my house. The dying process is super easy. All you need is a container of some kind, water, dye and the flowers. You just add the 1oz bottle of dye to the water, give it a good stir to combine and dip your flowers. That it is! They are dry and ready to go in 24 hours. The best part is the dye is super easy to clean up and doesn't stain your fingers. This project was super easy and I honestly already need more flowers and dye for another flower arrangements in my home.

caption:
This week, I was gifted parchment paper and a dutch oven from @kana.goods.  Their products are functional, yet sustainable.

Their parchment paper is made from wood pulp and is completely compostable and biodegradable. I plan on using it with my springform cake pans for easy clean up. Anyone have a birthday coming up? ğŸ˜‰

The dutch oven is made from high quality cast iron and I love the crisp white it adds to my kitchen. I've already used it a few times to cook and can tell it will last me a lifetime. Swipe right â¡ï¸ to see what I created for dinner last night. The Dutch oven is linked in my bio! #Ad #GoodsMadeBetter #PeerKana
-
ğ™²ğšğš›ğš›ğš’ğšğš ğš‚ğš‘ğš›ğš’ğš–ğš™ ğšğš’ğšœğš˜ğšğšğš˜ 
8 cups chicken stock
2 tbsp olive oil
2 onions, chopped
3 garlic cloves, chopped
3 cups arborio rice
1 tbsp curry powder
Grated zest of 1 lime
Juice of 1 lime
2/3 cup coconut milk
1 lb shrimp, peeled
1/4 cup basil leaves
1 tbsp chopped cilantro
Ground black pepper
Green onions, chopped
[1] In a large stock pot, bring stock to a boil and maintain at a simmer.
[2] Heat your dutch oven over medium-low heat. Add in your olive oil. Saute the onions and garlic until soft (3-4 min). Add in your curry powder and rice and mix well. Mix in lime zest and lime juice.
[3] Ladle in 1/2 cup of the chicken stock into your rice mixture until fully absorbed. Repeat this process until you use up the chicken stock. (~20 min)
[4] Add in shrimp and coconut milk. Mix well to make sure the coconut milk is absorbed. Add in basil and cilantro. Remove from heat and let sit for 5 min.
[5] Top with black pepper to taste and green onions as garnish.
-

caption:
Did everyone know that firm/extra firm tofu should be pressed? Apparently my family knew and no one told me ğŸ˜‚ My mom strained hers overnight in the fridge and my sister built a pressing contraption out of pots and pans (mind you, it would need to sit like that for hours). Luckily, I didnâ€™t need to experiment with that since @tofu.bud came along and gifted me this tofu press. All you have to do is place the tofu in between the plastic strainer pieces and turn the spring to lock it in place. It only takes 15 min to drain the tofu block. #gifted #tofubud #tofupress
-
What are the benefits of pressing tofu? It squeezes out the excess water from the container and allows the tofu to absorb all the flavors youâ€™re working with! Itâ€™ll also allow to enjoy its true texture.
-

When I talk to new creators or clients, thatâ€™s our first discussion. Once you get past the idea that vanity and popularity equal success, you can actually get some work done here.

So what do you need to start earningâ“Hereâ€™s what Iâ€™ve learned:

1. Flexibility. If youâ€™re passionate, find multiple ways to sell your content and your brand. Sponsored content, freelancing, consulting.

2. Consistency. If you give up before your spinning wheels catch, then of course it wonâ€™t happen.

3. Education mindset. Everything changes so quickly, so if youâ€™re not willing to keep learning and getting better, then youâ€™re just doing yourself a disservice. Stay ahead of the game so you can sell what you do.

4. Community. Maybe not directly linked, but finding people who make you feel less crazy because they get it AND build you up when you have that idea or ask for more is ğŸ”‘

Iâ€™m doubling down and going to be sharing more of what Iâ€™ve learned these last few years. Content collab course coming soon along with more yt videos on what you need to know weekly. PLUS, Iâ€™m giving tips daily on tiktok, so if youâ€™re over there come find me!

caption:
Hhhmmmm... I donâ€™t even know where to start.
First of, THIS IS NOT A PREGNANCY ANNOUNCEMENT â€” I WISH IT WAS THOUGHğŸ˜¢ğŸ™ğŸ¼

Late June, my Mom passed away from Metastatic Breast Cancer which she fought for 10years.ğŸ˜¢ I was heartbroken, still heartbroken.ğŸ’”ğŸ˜­ We all are. 

Two weeks later, I found out I was pregnant. My heart was pounding, hands were shaking, tears were falling and just had so much emotions in me. Sooo happy and sad at the same time. Happy because God finally answered our prayers but sad because Mommy wonâ€™t be able to meet another grand baby.ğŸ˜¢
Mommy whispered to God how much we wanted another baby...

That didnâ€™t last long. I had the slightest spotting just two weeks after I found out I was pregnant. It wasnâ€™t even bright red, just a pink tinged. I tried to stay positive but already had that bad feeling. I saw my OB early at 6weeks  and she only saw a sac, so she ordered a blood work to check my HCG levels and it was about 33,000+ which is good.ğŸ™ğŸ¼ So she did another ultrasound and saw a yolk sac and a tiny embryo with no cardiac activity. It was early so we were trying to stay positive and do another ultrasound the following week. I tell you, I spent so much time searching and watching for videos/stories with similar experience that had a positive outcome. At least just to give myself hope but there wasnâ€™t much. Despite that, I continued to pray and so did  family and close friends. I can see that my OB was also trying to stay positive for me since she knew my Mom just passed. She wanted to give me some good news... Fast forward after I had 4 transvaginal and 1 abdominal ultrasound, my OB confirmed that I had a miscarriage. She gave me an option if I want to wait, take a medication or have a D&C(Dilation & curettage). I bawledğŸ˜­ I just donâ€™t know what to do and why this is all happening. My Mom was an OB-Gyn and she would have been the perfect person to ask.ğŸ˜­ğŸ˜­ğŸ˜­
My heart didnâ€™t even had time to heal and now itâ€™s shattered again.ğŸ˜¢
 
...to be continued in comments. â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸

caption:
It was a strange morning, getting myself and the boys ready to actually go somewhere.  I kept thinking we were going on another drive thru experience, but we were actually headed to a real indoor pop up museum. Itâ€™s been a while!

I have to say, as much as I love wearing jammies and experiencing things from the comfort of my car, nothing, and I mean NOTHING, compares to actually walking inside of a museum and exploring. 
Especially, when itâ€™s safely done!

We were invited to visit the @3darmuseum in Santa Monica via @themommybloggertribe and are absolutely grateful for the experience. 

We arrived at our scheduled visit time and were greeted by the lovely staff and manager. Our temperatures were taken and I was kindly instructed to log on to their WiFi and download the app which turns every installation into a really awesome moving image. 

The space is large and there were only two other people scheduled at our visit time.  We didnâ€™t see the other guests after the checkin process, so it felt like we had the place to ourselves. 

Friends, it was FUN! I have to say, I was a little hesitant initially, because my boys canâ€™t stand how many pictures I take of them, but with the app and the amazing videos I was taking of them slaying dragons, playing football, and jumping volcanos, they couldnâ€™t wait to get to the next instillation.

caption:

caption: Ik werd altijd bewonderd voor het lef dat ik getoond had op 20-jarige leeftijd om te gaan voor mijn dromen. Gewoon doen wat mijn hart me vertelde. Stoppen met studeren, alleen gaan wonen, full-time beginnen werken in mijn eigen zaak. Dat heeft me altijd getypeerd de jaren nadien. Het werd deel van mijn identiteit. Laurentine, de durf-al. Laurentine zonder angst. Laurentine die zich overal gewoon in smijt. Armen open, ogen toe. Je kan je voorstellen hoe pijnlijk en frustrerend het was om dat deel van mezelf plots kwijt te zijn. Ik heb twee jaar gezocht en voel nu dat ze er terug is. Ik sta in mijn kracht omdat ik het idee los liet dat het perfect moet zijn. Dat ik nu al exact moet weten waar ik ga landen. Dat ik niet goed genoeg ben om te doen waar ik toe voorbestemd ben. Wat ik nu doe ligt zoveel dichter bij mijn ziel dan â€˜kleren verkopenâ€™ en het is daarom ook veel enger om daarin te ondernemen. Angst is een slechte raadgever. Beginnen moeten we altijd ergens. Natuurlijk zijn er mensen die meer opgeleid zijn. Natuurlijk zijn er mensen die al ongeveer doen wat jij wil doen. But no-one is you. And that is your power. âœ¨ quote by @dangerouswco

caption: Na een redelijk traumatische ervaring die voort kwam uit een Tinder-match, had ik er ff genoeg van. Sowieso vind ik al jaren weinig aan die app. Ik zit er nooit meer dan 2 weken op om dan weer te verwijderen voor maanden. Tinder roept bij mijn vriendinnen die vaker daten wel meer frustraties op. Vorige week hoorde ik een spannend verhaal van de ene vriendin en een romantisch van een andere. Ik dacht â€œgodverdomme, ik kan ook nog wel eens wat â€œthrillsâ€ gebruiken.â€ Onze beste vriend C & de getroffen maatregelen maakt het allemaal nogal eentonig, heÌ? Hoewel ik niet te klagen heb; ik doe elke dag met veel passie wat ik graag doe, ik kan super goed alleen zijn en voel me mega happy. Ook dat â€œverlangen naar een manâ€ duurt vaak niet langer dan een avond. Maar goed, los daarvan. Tinder. Je downloadt dat. Zet er een paar leuke fotoâ€™s op. Ik had deze ook genomen want ja, happy vibes, eentje met zonnebril mocht ook wel, vriendin dabei, feestje (= kijk, ik ben fun)... Je hoort dan eigenlijk iets in je â€œbioâ€ te schrijven maar eerlijk, daar begin ik zelfs niet aan. How the fuck moet ik waar ik voor sta en wie ik ben daarin samenvatten? Je kan ook gaan voor een gevat zinnetje ofzo maar als ze dat dan verkeerd interpreteren? Er is geen context. Je ziet enkel fotoâ€™s. En dan ga je dus swipen. Oh. Oh man. Wat je allemaal tegenkomt. Het blijft me verbazen. Nu ja, er moet voor ieder wat wils zijn zeker? En op ieder potje zou blijkbaar een dekseltje passen. Een minimaal aantal keer swipe ik rechts. Oh, een match. Leuk. Komt er ofwel niets uit hun digitale mond ofwel zeggen ze iets dat me meteen mateloos irriteert. Of ze zijn lief, tof en enthousiast en toch denk ik â€œnahhhâ€. Hoe oppervlakkig is het ook eigenlijk om alleen op je uiterlijk beoordeeld te worden en omgekeerd? Ik denk dat veel potjes en dekseltjes elkaar daarom mislopen op zoâ€™n app. Geef mij maar de toevallige ontmoeting (moeilijk these days haha). Maar kijk, het zal vast en zeker aan mij liggen. Of aan het feit dat ik niet â€œop zoekâ€ ben. Want dan hoor ik eigenlijk niet erop te zitten. Hoe dan ook heb ik de app liever niet op mijn gsm. Ik heb er deze week een uur van mijn leven aan verloren. ğŸ¤·ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸ Who feels me?

caption: Het is niet goed gesteld met het mentaal welzijn van jongeren. ğŸ¥º @stadsintniklaas deed een enqueÌ‚te en daaruit bleek ze zich vaak alleen voelen, de meesten zien de examenperiode niet zitten en 5% kan bij niemand terecht met hun problemen. ğŸŒ§ Ik zoom-de (is dat nu een werkwoord of niet?) heel de week met klassen van het 5e en 6e middelbaar om hen een beetje moed in te spreken, selfcare tips te geven en de verschillende instanties waar ze terecht kunnen toe te lichten. ğŸ™ @baasinsintniklaas richtte hier speciaal een nieuw initiatief voor op: Jong Wild Goud. Waar dit â€œhoe is â€™t?â€ project het eerste van was. Dit is geen ad maar iets wat ik zelf wil delen. âœŒï¸Omdat de jongeren zich niet gehoord voelen. Er wordt weinig rekening gehouden met waar zij nu door moeten. Wat zij voelen. Wat zij denken. In het Tejohuis kunnen ze terecht voor 10 gratis & anonieme pyschologische begeleidingssessies. Ik hoop oprecht dat ze mijn tips gaan toepassen & daar langs gaan. De belangrijkste boodschap die ik meegegeven heb is dat ze niet alleen zijn. En dat naar een psycholoog gaan helemaal niets is om u voor te schamen. Dat ik het al doe van toen ik 16 was. caption:
Exact dit. Tijd om het tij te keren. Tijd om te stoppen met over-werken te idealiseren. Ook ik heb mezelf moeten ontdoen van het aangeleerde non-stop bezig zijn waar ik mee ben opgegroeid. Hard werken was het minimum. Tijd voor jezelf nemen onbestaande. Maar er is helemaal niks â€˜coolâ€™ aan uzelf kapot werken en gaan tot je niet meer kan. caption:
Hetgeen wat zich nu manifesteert is niet iets wat er plots was. Al meer dan 2 jaar had ik het @_glowcommunity_ idee en toch startte ik niet. Degene die me up-close volgen weten dat dit gepaard ging met soms zware highs maar vaak ook enorme lows. Zoals het leven, natuurlijk. Maar nog meer met - naar mijn gevoel - â€œeen beetje aanmodderenâ€. Zingeving ontbrak. â€œWat ben ik eigenlijk aan het doen met mijn leven?!â€ Ik had de vrijheid die ik altijd al wou en het toch gaf het me geen voldoening. Ik wist wat ik wou en ook wat ik daarvoor moest doen en ondernam geen actie. Dat FRUSTREERDE (met hoofdletters ja) me ELKE FUCKING DAG. Ondertussen zag ik bij andere mensen wel zaadjes geplant worden. Soms zaadjes die een mini-beetje leken op het plantje dat ik wou. Ook dat was lastig. Ik probeerde vast te houden aan â€œenjoy the journey, enjoy the journeyâ€ omdat ik wist dat ik op een dag terug ging kijken en snappen waarom het allemaal zo moest gebeuren. Dat was niet makkelijk. Dat was heel, heel, heel moeilijk. En toch bleef ik trouw aan mezelf. Ik plooide niet voor wat er van mij verwacht werd door de maatschappij. I sat with myself. Ik leerde. Ik groeide. Non-stop. De momenten dat je vast zit zijn de grootste leermomenten. Als ik 2 jaar geleden met mijn project gestart was, had het nooit dezelfde waarde gehad als nu. Looking back; the dots connect, always. En het was elke traan en frustratie waard. Ik dacht dat ik stil stond maar ik vloog. Richting dit moment. READY TO GLOW âœ¨ #issamood

Ik zat hier net in mijn zetel te kijken naar het kaarslicht dat danst en kreeg kippenvel. Een rust viel over mij en de â€˜zorgeloosheidâ€™ die ik altijd wou - is er. Bedankt dat je steeds voor mij bleef zorgen, ook al had ik het niet altijd makkelijk om jou te aanvaarden. Je bleef mij dragen. Tijdens de dagen dat ik je als 13-jarige enkel crackers en perziken gunde. Tijdens de dagen dat jij mijn middel van controle was. Tijdens de avonden dat alles wat ik â€˜te veel atâ€™, ook weer uit jou moest. Bedankt om er zelfs dan nog te blijven zijn voor mij. We heelden, herstelden en groeiden samen. Wat een opluchting moet dat voor jou zijn geweest. En voor mij, want ik ontdekte dat jij niet tegen mij werkt, maar samen met mij. Bedankt om mij te leren inzien wanneer ik rust moet nemen. Vandaag luister ik meer dan ooit naar jou. Bedankt om mij door trauma te loodsen. Je werkt eÌcht op miraculeuze wijze. Bedankt om mij telkens de signalen te sturen die ik nodig heb. Samen vinden wij altijd een oplossing. Bedankt voor de tranen die je laat vloeien wanneer ik daar nood aan heb. Bedankt voor mijn ongelooflijk brede lach, ondanks mijn dunne lippen. Bedankt voor alles wat mij â€˜mijâ€™ maakt. Bedankt voor alles wat ik dankzij jou kan doen. Bedankt om mij te beschermen. Bedankt voor de kleine en grote wonderen die ik samen met jou beleef. Bedankt. Vandaag zijn we samen sterker dan ooit wantâ€¦ ik aanvaard je. Ik zorg voor je. Ik heb je lief. Ik koester je. Ik hou van je.

caption: Het is mentaal zwaar voor velen. Ik merk het in de DMâ€™s die ik krijg. Ik merk het aan vrienden. Ik merk het hier bij mensen die ik volg op social media. De ontelbare redenen waarom het zwaar is, daar hebben we weinig aan. Waar we wel iets aan hebben, is elkaar. Praat met elkaar. Vraag uw vrienden hoe het met ze gaat. Stuur kaartjes. Wees je eigen beste vriend. Zoek naar het moois in elke dag. Check het nieuws niet. Ga de natuur in. Zet uw favoriet liedje op en dans. Laat uw gevoelens toe en de tranen rollen; je hoeft niet elke dag sterk te zijn. Mediteer of doe een poging tot; niemand is pro in iets wat hij voor de eerste keer doet. Bestel verf en schilder. Leg een puzzel. Beperk uw social media gebruik. Zoek iets om je op te focussen; een doel, een nieuwe passie, een project, iets wat je wil bijleren. Lees een roman of leer uit een selfhelpbook. Daag jezelf uit en doorbreek patronen, leer jezelf een nieuwe gewoonte aan. De afleiding is nog nooit zo minimaal geweest. Er is veel wat niet kan maar er is ook nog veel wat wel kan. En like nu niet alleen deze post. Doe het. Sommige dingen zullen oncomfortabel aanvoelen omdat je er nooit eerder tijd voor nam of â€˜omdat je gewoon geen zin hebtâ€™. Maar je moet me geloven als ik zeg dat je je achteraf beter gaat voelen. ğŸ’›âœ¨

caption:
Today we celebrate Thanksgiving. This year has been so different and felt so weird. Normally on Thanksgiving we would be gathered at our house all 40 or so of our family members around a table sharing laughs and a meal. (Yâ€™all know my family is like the Griswolds itâ€™s always a party) This year we are on the road to the mountains to celebrate Thanksgiving just the 4 of us. If weâ€™ve learned anything this year itâ€™s learning to adjust and roll with the punches. Iâ€™m learning to let go of the control because letâ€™s face it, none of us are in control. 
.
Iâ€™m thankful for the gift of time this year. Weâ€™ve had so much more of it as a family. (And you probably have too) Even though in the early stages of quarantine all there was to look forward to was taking a bike ride or taking a family walk, Iâ€™m thankful for that quality time that I normally would have taken for granted. 
.
Weâ€™ve taught our kids that it doesnâ€™t really matter where we are on Thanksgiving (on the road, in a hotel, or just sitting at home) as long as we have each other thatâ€™s whatâ€™s important. I think Iâ€™m learning this too. 
.
I also believe this horrible virus has taught many of us how short life really is. Let go of anger. Forgive that person who wronged you. Take the time to tell your loved ones you love them. Itâ€™s just not worth holding onto anger or resentment.  Call up your family and tell them you love them today. 
.
.From my family to yours, Happy Thanksgiving. I am very grateful for you all and this wonderful community that I consider a second family. â™¥ï¸

.
.
i am grateful for COVID: it brought my family home from overseas for over a month. it showed me what relationships were real + which werenâ€™t. it showed me the value of HEALTH. SAFETY. SECURITY. I am grateful for hard + honest conversations. Iâ€™m grateful for feedback on how Iâ€™m perceived. how I made you feel. how something I said didnâ€™t sit right. And I am particularly grateful for the strong FIERCE WOMEN bold enough to give it to me. not bc theyre biting back. but bc they care.

caption:
why is she posting about @kevinlove ?
.
.
for those of you who donâ€™t know - Kevin Love is an NBA player for the Cleveland Cavs. yesterday he released an interview about his heart breaking struggle with mental illness. his suicidal thoughts, his feelings on inadequacy. his imposter syndrome. of all this he shared - hereâ€™s what got me :
.
.
Kevin love is 6â€™8â€. Heâ€™s 251 pounds of solid muscle. he makes $31 million a year playing in the NBA. one paper Kevin Love is the physical definition of strong. he is undeniably successful. insanely healthy. 
.
.
yet, everyday he struggles with depression + on really bad days - suicidal thoughts. Kevin Love LOOKS (key word here) exactly the opposite of how he feels.
.
.
so it got me thinking - how often do we look at someone and judge them. how often do we NOT understand:
- the pretty girl that feels ugly
- the skinny person who feels fat
- the anxious person who seems calm
- the depressed person who seems happy
.
.
this reminder that we are NOT WHAT WE LOOK LIKE is exactly what we need. now. yesterday. tomorrow.
.
.
be kind. be compassionate. truly try to understand that how we look is so often not how we feel. & when you learn more - do better. 
.
.
.
.
.
.

caption:
This is the serious face of a serious tree hunter. In previous years Otto fell asleep on our way to the neighbors tree farm. Isn't that how it always goes? He woke up grouchy, we'd grab a precut and head home. â â €
This year he was determined to find the best tree in the field. We ran from tree to tree for well over an hour until Otto found the one. It was missing about half it's branches in the middle but I thought meh might be good for bigger ornaments. â â €
Joe hacked it down, we yelled TIMBER and we drug it to the wagon. â â €
We carried our prized tree into the house only to discover we, once again, bought a tree 8 inches too tall. â â €

caption:
We headed out this weekend to pick up what I believe will be the last of our garland order. Each year we wrap the front porch and fireplaces in fresh greenery with big red bows. â â €
It's a tradition that I love coming home to each night and one that Joe curses because he's the one who has to hang it up and take it down. â â €
We have the tree up in the corner and will be spending the rest of the week decorating it with my delicate collection of Shiny Brite ornaments. â â €
I always treat myself to a "replacement box" because as gentle as Otto is with them, we are bound to have a few casualties. He loves to help and is so good about being careful that he gets devastated when one shatters. That's when we head for the back ups. â â €
I absolutely love that he always wants to help. My favorite is when Otto says "let me give you a hand with that mom" . â â €
I think the best part of decorating this weekend was explaining to Otto that we cut the tree down from outside and bring it inside. That was a conversation we had a few different times. Toddlers at Christmas might just be the best thing ever. â â €
#adventuresinabbyland #teamottoâ â €

caption:
I'm doing everything that I can to make this weird holiday season the best ever. I am fighting the sadness of the missing pieces this year but when I really think about the pieces I'm most sad about, they're not what the season is about at all. â â €
I am sad that this year Otto is head over heels in love with Christmas and we won't be doing the big family get togethers, the trips to the parades or even to sit on Santas lap. â â €
As a parent it's hard to not want to give your child the world especially at Christmas. However, Christmas is not about Santa, Christmas lights or toys. It's about the birth of Jesus and the meaning behind him coming into the world. It's been an interesting lesson trying to teach Otto. He loves the nativity scene but hasn't quite grasped that the baby's name is Jesus. He keeps referring to the set as Mary, Joseph and Lisa. As you can see we have some work to do. â â €
It's ok to be sad about the missing pieces but it's important to remember they don't complete the puzzle. â â €

caption:
Thanksgiving 2020 is in the books and now we decorate and wait for Santa to come. â â €
We have been having an absolute riot with Otto this holiday season. He looks for Santa's sleigh every night before going to bed and every creak of the old roof could be him. â â €
I just love this age (despite all the stubbornness). â â €
When we were at the apple orchard this little shed was packed full of Christmas decorations and Otto was absolutely convinced that it was Santas workshop. He made us stand here and look for elves for a good ten minutes. â â €
His new favorite question other than asking someone's name is asking what they would like for Christmas. â â €
He says he wants a Paw Patrol Dino Rescue, Mom wants a purse and Dad wants a basketball. â â €
It's funny because Otto secretly also wants a basketball and knows his mama wants that purse. â â €
I'm excited to welcome in the holiday season. For now I'll be Black Friday shopping from the sofa! â â €

caption:
Thanksgiving plans are canceled but Thanksgiving goes on. With everything going on with Covid right now Joe and I thought it would be best for us to stay home. â â €
It really stings. â â €
It stings to have to avoid your own family on the holiday where you are most grateful for them. â â €
All is not lost. Joe and I frantically found some turkey legs at the local butcher and we went to the market yesterday to get some vegetables. Thanksgiving for three is on the menu today and we are going to celebrate the many blessings that have been given to us. â â €
We are getting dressed up for our "private" Thanksgiving feast before watching some football and going for a walk (weather pending). â â €
We never ever have a quiet holiday so we are trying to take this as hopefully the only opportunity we'll have for one. â â €
Wherever you are celebrating today friends I hope you are celebrating. I am thankful for you, my friends and family. God is good. Happy Thanksgiving. (and 2020, I'm most thankful you have only one month left)â â €

caption:
Am I the only one who gets overly excited for birthday coupons during the month of their birthday? â â €
Every year I get my @freepeople birthday coupon and I splurge on a few key pieces to add to my wardrobe. When I look at some of my favorite sweaters still hanging in my closet, most of them were purchased with my birthday coupon. â â €
This sweater here was a birthday purchase and I'm honestly debating about getting one more color. I went back and forth about which size (medium or large) but in the end went with the large because I wanted to wear it as a sweater dress (and I don't like things too short). â â €
Typically this time of year I'm stocking up on sequins and tulle (and trust me there is still some of that going on) but since much of this winter will most likely be spent at home, I've leaned more into the cozy, well made sweaters. â â €
This sweater will be perfect for after the Thanksgiving feast! â â €

caption:
It's Friday and this elf and I have some work to do!â â €
â â €
This weekend's Christmas project is getting rid of the pumpkins on the porch, assembling my vintage aluminum tree, and getting a space ready for our real tree in the living room. â â €
This seems like not a big task but between Otto and I's collections... It's a task. â â €
Basically it involves finding a cute space to shove all of our crap until the tree comes down in January and the clutter can be restored to it's original resting space. â â €
Little does Otto know that when he's not looking I sneak toys he no longer plays with into the donation box. I would feel bad about it but I'm pretty sure that is the same thing Joe is doing to me. â â €
I will say though, spending all of this time at home I've tackled quite a few cluttered drawers. Folding, stacking and sizing and just throwing away has really helped (mostly my kitchen) stay organized. â â €
Organized being a term used loosely around here. â â €
â â €
Regardless, It is a weekend of fun and family time (again) and I'm grateful for the sun that is forecasted our way! â â €
â â €

caption:
This post is #sponsored by @michiganhhs. When Otto got his flu shot in September, we had to go to the toy store because he was so brave. It was hard not to smile because when Nurse J offered him a Mickey sticker after his shot he took the entire packet of them, hopped off the table and said, â€œWeâ€™re going to the toy storeâ€. There is no debating with a toddler. Instead of picking out a small car like we usually do after a doctorâ€™s appointment he told me it was a â€œspecial dayâ€ and picked out the semi hauler.  He proudly showed off his Band-Aid to everyone and told of his tales of bravery. Now, more than ever itâ€™s important to get the flu shot. With COVID-19 already overwhelming our hospital systems itâ€™s important to take as much pressure off of our healthcare workers as possible. A flu vaccination has been shown to reduce the risk of having to go to the doctor due to the flu by 40 to 60 percent. Itâ€™s also important to get the vaccination as soon as possible because it can take your body up to two weeks to build immunity to the flu after your shot. I was someone who never used to get a flu shot because I was young and healthy, but when Otto was born we learned more about protecting him and other vulnerable members of our society. When you get your flu vaccination you reduce the risk of spreading it to others who could be vulnerable themselves or taking care of vulnerable people. â â €
For more information about the flu vaccine check out my stories! #gotMiVax #IVaccinateâ â €

caption:
Otto has been loving all of this time at home. We go for walks, play outside when it's not too cold and windy and he gets to play with his toys while his parents work. â â €
We have I think once again struck a balance of working from home. We had a breath of somewhat normalcy for a bit, but we know how to do this quarantine thing. â â €
It's not as strict as it was in the Spring. This three week long scale back still allows us to get take out, going for drives, going to the outdoor farmers markets and supporting small businesses in our area. â â €
This past Saturday we went to the fall farmers market in Holland and stocked up on cheese, root veggies, donuts and fresh garland. We are going to go back again on Wednesday to get more greenery because, you can never have enough greens!â â €
We are nearing the end of 2020 and hopefully each day is a step in the right direction. Who knows what next year will look like but i'm holding on to hope that it only gets better from here! â â €

caption:
I miss Sunday brunches out. We are taking extra precautions with Covid again as cases are still on the rise. We still get take out from all of our favorites but I miss the noise, getting dressed up and enjoying a meal that I don't have to clean up. â â €
I'm buying stock in sweatpants and maxi dresses because 2021 is going to be the year of dining out. â â €
I keep telling myself that things continue to improve around here. Back in April when we would get take out we would wipe down all of the containers and the counter and basically wear gloves to move it to a plate. It seems crazy to look back on that but we have to to see how far we've come. Scientist, doctors and nurses know so much more about the virus now than they did when it first hit. â â €
I'm working hard on keeping positive and remaining optimistic that if we continue to do the work and be safe things will only continue to get better! Now...what's for dinner? â â €

caption:
I can't believe @TheFoundCottage has been open for an entire week now since our holiday reset. â â €
It was an interesting time to say the least. Decorating the shop for Christmas is the absolute funnest time at the store and typically the most stressful. This year compound the stress by 1000X. â â €
Owning a small business during 2020 has not been easy. We were shut down for three months this spring, allowed to open in steps by appointments and then limited capacity. â â €
We implemented hand sanitizing stations, temperature checks and all of the other hurdles to jump to keep our staff and customers safe and healthy. â â €
We are all holding our breath right now praying to be able to continue to stay open as much as the holiday season as possible. We thought we were scrappy in 2019... but learned what that really meant in 2020. â â €
If you are starting to do your holiday shopping please keep your local small business in mind. We are all here for you! â â €

caption:
When times get tough I have a tendency to put my nose to the ground and just try to plough through it, not asking for help and not relying on my faith or God. It's gotten me in trouble so many times throughout my life and yet I continue to do it over and over again. â â €
I caught myself doing it again this week as we head into the holiday season around here. Otto is out of daycare for now, Joe and I are working in shifts. Things are so hectic! I caught myself continuously waking up at 4:30am and rather than trying to get much needed rest, sleep or even devotions, my computer was popped right open and I was plugging away at emails. â â €
Every. Single. Time. However rather than wait until things implode around me because of this behavior I'm trying to make small changes into how I approach this season. â â €
It has been so helpful to write out the following:â â €
Daily Schedule â â €
5 tasks to tackleâ â €
2 things to do while on a brain breakâ â €
The most important task though is taking time to be quiet and pray. â â €
My prayer today friends is that we all find peace, safety and health throughout this holiday and winter season. â â €

caption:
The best part of the morning is when Otto wakes up and looks to see who is still in the bed and then declares "It's best friends day!" (if all three of us are still there). So that is what today is. Best friends day. We are again going to take advantage of this sunny weather and play outside, maybe smoke some meat and act like it's still summer. â â €
We still have some bulbs to get in the ground and I think that these warm temps are sounding their warning bells.â â €
I'm excited to get one more garden activity in without freezing my hands off.â â €
It's yet another lesson the garden can teach you. Do the dirty work now and come spring you will hopefully have a bounty of beautiful blooms from the ground. â â €
I'm putting these bulbs in the ground because it confirms that spring will come eventually.â â €
But for now we wait in the calm stillness of fall transitioning into winter.â â €
Happy Sunday Friends. â â €

caption:
New hair, New makeupâ¤
CatriceCosmetics gifted me with some goodies to review! I've never used this brand before but wasn't disappointed with their products! 
.
My favorite was the eye shadow palette even though one of the shimmer shades were broken, the colors where perfect for neutral or full glam look, good pigments and both shimmer and matte shades. 
.
I was also sent a primer and priming glowing spray has this beautiful rose gold shimmer in it. But honestly wish I would have seen a little more bluring from the actual primer.
.
I would have choose a lighter concealer as it was a tad dark for my color at the moment but it had no trouble covering redness and dark circles under my eye and the foundation was a perfect match and full coverage corrected the darker concealer.
.
Over all my thoughts on 
@catrice.us are more positive than negative. And I would recommend this brand. Though I'd suggest maybe buying the palettes instore to be sure of no broken shades.

caption:
In less than a month I will make my goal of breastfeeding till age 2!

caption:
Some days are good and some are bad, but there is good in everyday.
.
I have been struggling with my anxiety  lately. More than what it usually is but I'm working on it.
.
The other week, completely loosing it with a full blown anxiety attack. 
Luckily, I was completely alone (never happens) 
I decided I didn't want to get out at one of the errands we had to run and the boys went with their dad.
An i got a moment to myself.. right?.. i guess you could say that....
Im grateful they didn't experience this with me.
.
I was fine one sec then out of no where when I say I lost it, I lost Control... out of No Where... 
Like a wave of emotions 
 +panic resulting in hyperventilating  turned into in tingling sensations  leading to  numbness and actual lose of control in part of my face...
Nothing like anything I've experienced before.
The worst of it lasting about 15 minutes but in all about 45 till I finally calmed down.
Then leaving me completely dranined,
And overwhelmed...
And they all came out with goodies to show and suspected nothing.
.
I'd like to think some days im super mom but some days I'm far from it.
Its easier said than done to just to release all the worry, anxiety, and stress..
What got me through that moment was opening up my Bible app reading scriptures and some serious time spent praying. While I was physically alone I didn't feel alone. 
.
Can all your worries add a single moment to your life?
Luke 12:25 
.
Worry weighs a person down; an encouraging word cheers a person up.
Proverbs 12:25 
.
Donâ€™t be afraid, for I am with you. Donâ€™t be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you. I will hold you up with my victorious right hand.
Isaiah 41:10

caption:
Spent the weekend celebrating my middle baby's Birthday! 
Who likes throwing Birthday partys?ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸
not me..
While it may not look it, I was stressed to the max ! I even hate to admit it, but as the party was starting I was ready to cancel it. ( I was even experiencing some panic attacks) .
Problem. after problem kept occurring. 
When I thought I completely prepared staying up till the wee am hours, making sure it was all ready...
.
While the normal worry of who actually is gonna show up is the issue this time, everything else was the problem... and that..
.
 the heat, no shade and having nothing set up outside in time...
from me being late to even set up to constantly forgetting things having to leave several times (yes even with kids with the party guest), wrong size balloons (also them popping as quick as I'm getting them blown from the heat.. ending up having to do it all by myself bc hubs gets a mandatory call into to work.... on and on I could sit here 
and tell all the way this party did not go as I planned..
.
I felt as if I had failed (as I have felt the last several partys but this time way worse). The pressure and guilt (guilt from skipping one of his other partys as well...) was literally eating me alive.
.
maybe to you some of these were minor details but pretty major to me...at the moment.
.
but through it all I tried to smile and just apologize the whole time and I survived!
.
 By the end of it all I was exhausted and drained and started realizing my Perspective was all 
WRONG.
.
I put all the little footage I got together and was so overwhelmed, 
bc it confirmed everyone else seemed to be enjoying themselves and the kids were having fun despite all the 'stressors' I was experiencing .
Mamas try to not be so hard on yourself.
ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
IT DOES NOT HAVE TO BE A PINTEREST BIRTHDAY PARTY!
ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
^^^^^read that again^^^^
.
your kids will probably not remember the hiccups (though your in laws mightğŸ˜‚I'm sure they understand)
.
Dont stress, its gonna turn out like its gonna turn out , sorry...but you cant control it all... just try to smile and enjoy it for what it is and these moments your creating bc you cant change the past.
â¤

caption:
A few books on my shelf that have meant so much to me the last couple months. If you have given me a book, a song, a poem, or an impression, please know you are my people, and it has meant the world to me. â™¡ Â Â â €
â €
Before everything happened with Collin I had listened The Dutch House. I loved it so much I ordered a hard copy and planned on reading it again as soon as it arrived. I am not a re-reader so *that* is how much I loved it. I jot little notes down for the reviews and pulled them up to write this post. It had said â€œThe sweetest story of a funny brother and his sister. Will break and remake your heart.â€ Not sure I can bring myself to re-read it right now, if youâ€™ve read it you know why, but no wonder I loved it so much. Also, Tom Hanksâ€™ narration is actual perfection.â €
â €
The other three books were gifted to me and I would highly recommend if youâ€™re going through a loss or need a way to support someone who is. Francis Weller is a freakinâ€™ treasure. And the Year of Magical Thinking is as well. And Motherâ€™s Milk is a specific kind of comfort, but something that has been on my mind so much. â €
â €
I posted the rest of my book reviews on my site, 2 of which made my top 3 for 2020 which were The Dutch House, American Dirt and The Heartâ€™s Invisible Furies. What was your favorite read this year? #smallfrybooks #bookstack

caption:
FAMILY - deep breaths.
â €
My single greatest teacher in this life. It has taught me to love without expectation, to forgive and protect, to apologize and try again, to set boundaries and hold to them. My most important lesson being to honor and respect where my family is in their own healing. To not push or prod, to just let them be. I feel really blessed (and poor, as it took a lot of therapyğŸ’¸) to feel nothing but love. Is it easy? Heck no. But, I hold no anger or ill will.â €

 When my parents split the divorce was nasty. I canâ€™t imagine divorce as a kid, but as a young adult, it hurt. A lot. We lost our sense of home, and we all sort of spun out into our own directions. Collin was the one who came to me and said, â€œThatâ€™s it! Weâ€™re starting Kartchner 2.0. For whoever wants to show up and be a family.â€ And limping and bruised we did just that. We all had to step into roles we werenâ€™t necessarily built for, and lift where we stood, even when hurting and angry â€” we showed up. â €
Some of my most sacred experiences came from the ashes of a family burned. Walking my sister down the aisle. Standing by my brother as he got sober. Sobbing with my sisters in a pile on the floor at my house, unable to stand another second, heartbroken for our brother. And Iâ€™m only just skimming the surface of whatever Collin has in store for me now. How amazing to know the some of our best days havenâ€™t happened yet?!â €
â €
Itâ€™s not a great feeling to know that the complexities of your family are being discussed on forums and by strangers (Not reading word of it, donâ€™t worry.) No one except us will ever know the truth, and thatâ€™s okay, because truly itâ€™s nunya. ğŸ˜‰â €
But, I just wanted to share this today because I know the Holidays for many are painful. Itâ€™s hard to see seemingly picture perfect families and wonder why we struggle so hard. But I know firsthand there is beauty in the ashes. There can be healing even when no one is saying sorry. And you are not alone. 

To my parents, Chad, Keira, Charity, Tim, Collin, Liz, Russ, Bethany, Lauren, Casey and everyone weâ€™ve given life to since, thank you for being my family. I love you all. #givethanks #lovelikecollin

caption:
When we first moved to our small town a couple years ago I prayed around the clock that my boys would find friends here. They have now, but at the time, it wasnâ€™t smooth sailing. I would take it super hard when they didnâ€™t hit it off with someone, and at my lowest, felt like we made a big mistake. If we were supposed to be here, shouldnâ€™t it be easier?â €
â €
Not long after, a neighbor Abby mentioned having Cal play with her son. I truly couldnâ€™t fit all of the challenges Ty and his little body have faced in this caption. Countless surgeries, specialists, medications, and more.Â Â He is unique in every way and I thought to myself and maybe even told AbbyğŸ™ˆ, â€œCalâ€™s just not your guy.â€ Heâ€™s an introvert and a loose cannon, and truly DGAFâ€™s about what anyone thinks of him. He once told me he wouldnâ€™t play with a boy because he smiled too much.ğŸ˜†ğŸ™‡ğŸ¼â€â™€ï¸ I thought I would save potentially hurting Abby or Tyâ€™s feelings, and to be honest, avoiding my own embarrassment at what might happen. I had long abandoned trying to fit Cal into the mold I had made for him. What I thought the world needed him to be. 
â €
Gratefully, Abby didnâ€™t give up and we finally got them together. Fast forward a couple of years and the Frames count ourselves so incredibly lucky. Lucky that we get to know and love Ty. Who makes every single one of us laugh until we have tears running down our faces. Who tells me I am so beautiful every time he sees me. Who entertains and plays with us through every church meeting, for hours in our home, and most importantly brings out the very best in Cal. The most happy, patient, imaginative, focused, silly Cal.â €
â €
Ty is my reminder of so many things: â €
â€¢To get out of my kidsâ€™ way. â €
â€¢Let them lead, but champion them every step of the way. (Abby taught me that)â €
â€¢That their (my, your) potential is limitless. â €
â€¢We are not our bodies, we are so, so much more. â €
â€¢To see things as God sees them. Because He answers our prayers and blesses us in his perfect way, even if we donâ€™t have the eyes to see it perfectly all the time.
â €
#givethanks

caption:
The last day Collin and I spent together I had texted him to see if Quincey would come to the pool with me. I was still in the weeds having my 4th baby and didnâ€™t feel up to the challenge to take them swimming alone. He wrote back, â€œYES! But weâ€™re all coming!!â€ ğŸ¤ Just him and I and our kids. â €
â €
He took Raleigh down the slide 15 times at least. Swam with the boys, wowed them with his diving board tricks (a jack knife right under the lifeguard getting them drenched was his specialty) and then while he thought no one was watching headed over to the concession stand. â €
He prepaid for 50 snow cones and then went to the corner to laugh to himself. ğŸ˜† News traveled fast and soon a line of stoked kids trailed out to the gate. ğŸ§ There are moments when I slip into shame that the last day we spent together was 2 months ago. Sure we texted memes like it was our job, but itâ€™s not the same right? How did I let that happen?! But then, I have to shake myself, and then I am overwhelmed with gratitude. It was the very best, last day. 

#lovelikecollin â €

â€¢â€¢â€¢ This story was taken from the life sketch I wrote for our familyâ€™s memorial. Itâ€™s on my site. A love letter from a sister to her big brother. Sharing these stories has been such a big part of my processing this whole week, thank you for being here and listening. I hope you donâ€™t feel like you have to keep sending condolences. I donâ€™t want to bring anyone down!! I just love talking about him, and itâ€™s brought me so much comfort. So thank you for that. â™¡

caption:
Weâ€™re all seeing his effect now, so you can imagine his effect when he dedicated 24/7 to the cause he believed in most. He served a two year service mission to Taipei, Taiwan for our church and at the time, you leave your family and you can write letters and call on Christmas and Motherâ€™s Day. Thatâ€™s it. Your day to day schedule is devoted to studying scripture, serving others, sharing the message of our church, working with those interested to join and, if all goes well, baptize them to be a member. In a notoriously uninterested country, Collin seemed to change hearts in droves. â €
â €
But in order to do that he had to leave his family (and Liz, they were dating for awhile by now!) for two years. You all know our side of the family is complicated and messy. We put the fun in dysfunctional. It has been for many years, and Collin was my rock through it all. The one I could turn to, forget my troubles and have a laugh. When he left in 1998, I was 12 and inconsolable. I cried every day for weeks. â €
â €
Tarzan was the movie of the day and Phil Collins gave us â€œYouâ€™ll be in my heart.â€ I recorded it to a tape and listened to it over and over and over, crying into the carpet. I harassed him via letters if he had heard it (are we seeing a theme?) and when he went to the airport to fly to Taiwan I got a phone call at the house. â €
â €
â€œHello?â€ â €

â€œ...Come stop your crying, it will be alright...â€ ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜­â €
â €
His voice sings through the receiver. And we both cry. I cry because I want my brother back. He cries, Iâ€™m sure, because heâ€™s scared, he is stepping into the unknown, and he knows what he has to do. â €
â €
His mission is bigger than than me. I know that now. It doesnâ€™t make it better, I would happily keep him to ourselves and deny all the good he can do. Iâ€™m angry. But now his endless talents know no limits. He is unbound, he is all love. â €
â €
Let him work in you. Let his message change your life. Know that he (and I) believe in a loving God, and even in all our crazy, our family will be together again. I wish it were tomorrow. #lovelikecollin

caption:
â €
People probably donâ€™t realize, but Collin is an amazing musician (save some talents for the rest of us.) He composed piano music, sang in the church choir and led the primary music for years. Guitar, cello, ukulele, you name it. â €
â €
When I got married in 2005, Coldplay had just released â€œFix Youâ€ and I was obsessed with it. I kept harassing him to learn it on the piano. And then at our wedding he surprised me and played and sang it for me. It has the register for a prepubescent altar boy, but he did it anyway. And I bawled.â €
â €
Fast forward to 10.20.2020, Russ and I are at our 15 year anniversary dinner eating at this hip restaurant (HSL, go itâ€™s so good) and itâ€™s playing banger after banger, all new indie rock songs that Iâ€™d have to secretly Shazam under the table. And then all the sudden, Fix You comes on. And we look at each other and we just smile. What are the odds? How amazing! It made us so freaking happy. â €
â €
I didnâ€™t know until later, but it was playing just as Collin left us. And to me, itâ€™s clear as day. Itâ€™s not a wedding song. But it was a big bear hug 15 years in the making and it has brought me so much comfort. â €
â €
Lights will guide you homeâ €
And ignite your bones â €
And I will try to fix you.â €
â €
#lovelikecollin â€” I know I keep asking you guys for stuff but, please share your memories. I (and Iâ€™m sure the rest of the family) would love to read them all someday when we need his big bear hugs most.

caption:
If I just keep running, moving, arranging, feeding, maybe the truth of this wonâ€™t ever hit me. And then when I finally sit and close my eyes, everything behind my lids is horrifying. We have so many questions, but mostly just the one: WHY. We want answers, but it seems we canâ€™t have them. Not yet anyway. In a world where everything is instant, we are learning to wait. To sit in it, to feel it all. â €
â €
In the waiting, I have seen and felt more goodness, more generosity, more support, love, and the true and lasting effect that Collin really had. It overflows and its ripple and radius has touched us all so deeply. â €
â €
I asked you to show up for him, for Liz and his kids, to let them hear us. And all your voices joined together and ROARED. I will never, ever forget it. I scrolled the donations with his kids and they laughed and cried and their jaws dropped. BLESS YOU ALL. Please pray for them, pray for Liz. If grief is the evidence of love, we now get a sense just how much they loved each other. And since there really is no right way to grieve, I might just have to share every last thing I love about my brother until my lungs give out. Thank you for waiting with us, for holding space, and for loving him like we do. xo, Emily #lovelikecollin
comments:
Losing a loved one is always hard - but more so when itâ€™s unexpected. My Dad just passed away in August. It was a long time coming but the grief is still unavoidable because we love him and miss him sooo much. It comes in waves.  Iâ€™ve found that when a wave hits - if I can take a break to lay in my hammock or in a quiet room and let myself feel/cry while I listen to his voice in some old recordings I have of him - Iâ€™m more quickly comforted. 
Iâ€™m so thankful that Collin was so vocal and so visible so that you have a wealth of recordings to draw from. Praying for and with your family.; At 32 I lost my brother to a car accident. He was my world. That was 1985. In 2016 I stumbled upon Collin, a guy on insta, having a laugh. It was like finding my brother all over again. I instantly bonded to him. My friends and family thought I was weird as I referred to him as my friend Collin. â€œCollin did this, Collin did that. Collin is exactly how Mike was. Imagine the two of them doing this together! Listen to Collin saving kids!â€ I DMâ€™d him regularly hoping to lift his spirit and encourage his work. The story where he sat behind the fast food restaurant and sobbed, gutted me. He deleted it very quickly but it was a glimpse of the burden a loving, giving heart held. I am almost as sad now as when my brother died. But itâ€™s not because I knew him, or even ever met him, but just chatted on occasion and said many many prayers for him and his family through the years. His love of life will not be forgotten. His smile and bright blue eyes will forever be in our hearts. I will do my best to love like Collin, hug like Collin. I can because of the brother gone in 1985 as well. caption:

I had (what I thought was) a stroke. Searing headache, lost feeling in my face, down my arms, legs and stomach, with slurred speech. I know now and am very familiar with these aura migraines, but then I had no clue what was happening to me. 

I crawled into bed, terrified and crying. Russ laid next to me, stroking my hair and sang me my favorite, most comforting gospel song. 

 â€œAbide with me â€˜tis eventide, the night is coming on... Within my heart a welcome guest, within my home abide. O savior stay this night with me, behold tis eventide.â€ 

Marriage, for us, hasnâ€™t been some magic cure-all, that solves all pain or loneliness.  But he has been the closest thing in my life to Christlike love. A witness to all the good, hard, and quiet. He has never tried to own or change or hurt. Just made himself the most welcome guest of my heart. That 19 year old girl didnâ€™t know how good she had it, but she knows now. Happy anni, Russ Frame â™¡

Mildly embarrassing, but then he tweeted out a link to my article about it and it became one of my favorite memories. (I also got in a tiny bit of trouble for singing â€œYouâ€™ll Be Backâ€ in the hallway of the hotel where the press junket was taking place, but thatâ€™s a whole â€˜nother story...)
All of this happened without me ever having seen #Hamilton in person. (Although Iâ€™d listened to the cast recording and mix-tapes a ridiculous number of times.) Finally, in 2018, I made it to the theater and was in the room where it happened. It lived up to every bit of the hype. ğŸ˜

caption:
A party without cake is just a meetingğŸ¤ª

Anyone else bake to relieve stress? Behold the brownie, Oreo Ice-cream cake with a Nutella-Oreo layer and topped with Ganache and more brownies and Oreos (of course!)

How I built it:

1) bake two brownie layers, I used @ghirardelli brownie mix

2) line a deep pan with parchment paper and transfer cooled brownie layer to the bottom

3) top brownie with Nutella and Oreo pieces

4) layer softened Oreo icecream on top 

5) freeze overnight

6) top icecream with Oreo crumbles and second brownie layer

7) drizzle chocolate ganache and decorate with brownies and Oreos!!

caption:
Riding that PR high today! Yesterday was supposed to be a 5k TT with some local women (similar to what we did a couple weeks ago) - but we decided to call it off with the rising COVID numbers. We all were bummed, but knew it was the best/safest decision.

I was tempted to do another solo 5k, but my coach suggested I pick another distance, if I was up for it. My body felt great all week, and I had done a mini taper...so when I woke up Saturday morning, I decided to shoot my shot at a 10k! I've only run a few 10ks in the past, and always thought of them as being really hard; I've never come anywhere close to low or sub-40...so going into it, thought a sub-40 would be a huge accomplishment.

I honestly have only run a handful of tempos with this new training...so thinking about a fast ~40 minutes of pain was VERY intimating. So it's probably good that I made a day-of decision. ğŸ˜‚ I chose to run on a track because I wanted the accurate distance and running laps seemed way more digestible than tackling 6 miles on the road (Type 2 fun...)

My goal was to shoot for 200s in 45-47 and quarters in 91-95...so when the slower range of that felt fast, I just told myself to hang on and stay tough. I hit the 5k in 19:26 and knew I'd def hit sub-40, and possibly even sub-39 (ğŸ¤¯) - but to stay relaxed. I literally said to myself, "don't be stupid and you'll PR no matter what." I felt my legs get lactic-y and lose power way before the aerobic system did; but was still able to find that second gear for the final mile, closing the final quarter in 82. ğŸŒ¶

Special thanks to @bose for helping propel me to my best 10k yet! The new Sport Earbuds sound amazing, DO NOT FALL OUT (ğŸ‰), are sweat/weather resistant...and, best of all, the battery life is impressive - up to 5 hours per charge. They also take phone calls (a must for me) and the audio for both the caller and receiver is great. As a lover of music/podcasts while running and lifting, I'm so thankful for these little buds! #BosePartner #BoseEarbuds #10kPR

caption:
Full send into a new week. Pain face included...because it's 2020. ğŸ’¥

Monday is actually my favorite day of the week (weird, I know). It means there's a whole week left to get shit done. But if I'm not efficient with my time, I start having a mini internal panic attack by Wednesday. As a perfectionist and someone who puts a lot of pressure on herself to succeed, the only way I survive is via mini goals and to do lists.

There's only 7 more Mondays left in 2020 and we get to make the decision as to how they unravel. There are so many things that have spiraled out of control in 2020; staying within ourselves to control what we can is at a new level of importance these days.

For the rest of the year, I'm choosing to control my attitude and my attention to details with my day-to-day tasks (coaching and personal training). Instead of looking at this year, thinking about how miserable it was, I'm choosing to look at the opportunities and silver linings it brought. 

So what are you choosing to control in these final weeks? What gratitude can you start honing in on as the end of another year approaches? #fullsend #happymonday #lululemonambassador #thesweatlife

caption:
My first 5k race on the track last Saturday was an experience!  As someone who never had any interest racing/getting faster in shorter distancesâ€¦Iâ€™ve gotta say, itâ€™s been really fun working on turnover. And having the opportunity to run against others in a safe, socially-distant race setting was a privilege!

Some of the main things I learned from the race:
â–«ï¸You ALWAYS have more than you think you do. The mind goes WAY before the legs do.
â–«ï¸Passing someone in a track race is a little scary, because you really have to commit to it. And itâ€™s also a bit overwhelming trying not to trip the people around you.
â–«ï¸There was a lap where I passed a high school girl and told her to stick to my shoulder and hang on. That lap went by faster than any other lap - turns out when you focus on doing something for the good of someone else, it really does make your own effort feel easy.
â–«ï¸5ks are painful.

Today, Iâ€™m sharing a full recap on my blog (link in profile); and I also include a quick review of the @brooks Adrenaline GTS 21, delivered to me from @zappos! Iâ€™ve officially added Brooks back to my shoe rotation because of how supported the shoes make me feel - and the Brooks Adrenaline is no exception to this.

caption:
Q: Which strength exercises should I do as a runner?
A: ALL OF THEM

If there's one thing you need to remember, it's that lifting and strength training will make you a stronger overall ATHLETE. Period. The goal as a runner should not be, "let me just get this calf stronger," or "let me work on my 'bad' knee."

You have to lift heavy to be strong and to move/perform like the badass athlete you are. Period.

This means upper and lower body. When you bench or row, there are absolutely carryovers into running, and I'm not just talking about using your arms to propel you up a hill. Upper body work yields major neuromuscular adaptations that will make your trunk and back stronger. The stronger you are up the entire chain, the better you're able to combat the forces that pound on your joints with every running step. 

It's not about adding lifting to your training randomly. It's literally about realizing that strength is part of your training, and it must fit in if you want to be successful long term. 

Video is of my PR bench of 120 lbs last night. Pow. ğŸ’¥ #stronglikearunner #runstrong

caption:
A year ago, I was 4 months postpartum. This weekend I ran the fastest 5k of my life - 55 seconds faster vs. pre-baby. But recovering from having a baby was above and beyond my expectations; that shit is HARD.

I felt so weak.
My back hurt.
I was tired from lack of sleep.
My boobs hurt.
Any previous injury i ever had suddenly popped up and intensified (HELLO cyst in my wrist + a neuroma in my foot).
Running wasn't enjoyable because it hurt. So I didn't for a long time.

The secret to coming back stronger? There is none. I threw out expectations. I rode the lows with the highs. I took unplanned rest days. I asked for help. I ignored pace. I stopped comparing myself to my old self. And I kept believing.

This process took a while. So if there's one thing you remember it's this: good things take time and a lot of belief. Keep showing up. Reassess every few months. Make sure you're seeing small improvements, and remember to celebrate the crap out of them. And find people who support you along the way and you'll never stop growing. #belief #perspective #swapteam #liftrunperform

caption:
In-run fueling is a low hanging fruit for SO MANY athletes. The concept of eating 200 kcal/hr seems simple (a GENERAL suggestion) - but actually training your stomach for that isâ€¦another story. But remember that the stomach is trainable, just like the rest of the body. Eating while running is typically not an innate trait weâ€™re born withâ€¦but we can teach ourselves how! 

So, in general, here are some tips for athletes when it comes to getting better about fueling on the run:
â–ªï¸Donâ€™t be afraid of trying different fuel types. Every body is going to respond differently to different energy sources.
â–ªï¸Eat before you run! That means eating breakfast should be a non-negotiable.
â–ªï¸There are no rules about HOW to eat while running (eg - you donâ€™t need to chow it all down at once) - if you need to take small bites/sips of whatever youâ€™re fueling with, then use that strategy!

Thanks to @clifbar for providing fuel that keeps me going during the day and also before my runs! Itâ€™s become an absolute staple in my diet, and its ingredients are simple, yet satisfyingâ€¦so I know itâ€™s a â€œsafeâ€ pre-run option for my gut.

caption:
â€œDo you eat less on rest days?â€

Thatâ€™s â¬†ï¸ a question I get asked a lotâ€¦and my answer: NO. In fact, some rest days (or days where Iâ€™m lifting and not running), I find myself craving/eating more.

Why?

Often rest/non-run days come after a hard effort or workoutâ€¦so the likelihood of waking up the day after a hard effort and being in an energy deficit is fairly high.

And with the intention of the days around hard effort days being RECOVERY (because training should be polarized) - the #1 thing that is going to help with recovery is sleepâ€¦followed by a balanced diet of fats/carbs/protein. When training is at a high stress/load, the last thing someone would want to do is further that stress on the body by not eating enough.

Training like an athlete also means EATING like an athlete. And thatâ€™s something I (finally) take seriously, after years of unhealthy habits during high school/collegiate athletics.

So yeah. Iâ€™m smiling in this photo because Iâ€™m about to eat my daily @clifbar after my lifting session, and you could say Iâ€™m pretty jazzed about it. ğŸ¤—

caption:
Breakthroughs aren't about luck. They're about hard work. The kind of work that happens when you keep showing up, even when it sucks...even when you're tired...even when you wonder why you're doing it anymore.

They're about repeating positive behaviors.
Eliminating distractions.
Asking for help, and realizing that you don't know it all.
Finding the positivity out of every situation.
Patience.
Embracing the discomfort.
Loving yourself.

Along the way, people will shut you down. They'll insinuate that you and your goals aren't good enough. They'll project their issues and agenda onto you. And you might believe these people...the narcissists. It's human nature that their words will creep into your head and psych you out. In fact: these people will straight up knock you down.

But it's up to you to keep showing up. And if you do get knocked down...to learn from it. To persevere and let it fuel your fire. Because your own motivation runs so much deeper.

So to you who is working hard towards something: whether it's a running, professional, educational, or personal goal. Keep going. Keep repeating the behavior thatâ€™s moving you closer to your goals. Do the hard shit and lean into it. Realize your self worth and keep showing up for yourself - because you deserve it.

caption:
How do you define success? That's something I think about a lot, especially this past weekend when I visited home (Central NY) for the first time in well over a year. The trip felt extra special this time, because my son is old enough to explore and adventure and see what I saw growing up.

Our definition of success changes all the time. When I was younger, I defined success by having friends...playing in a sports game...getting an after school job...going to college. These days, I look at success as being able to relax on the weekend...accomplishing my training goals...being present for my baby.

James Clear writes, "Hard work is rarely enough without good strategy, but even the best strategy is useless without hard work."

I learned about hard work as a kid growing up. I was taught that working hard would bring success. And success should be something that's sought out because achieving goals tends to yield happiness. But what I've learned as I've gotten older is that success is measured differently each season of life; and that's ok/normal.

And what happens when we fail? I used to fear failure; I think as a product of my upbringing. Failure meant I wasn't enough. It meant my hard work was a waste.

But...turns out...I (we) am (are) all enough.

Hard work and success is what YOU make of it. Hard work makes us more resilient, stronger, and more determined. You generate your own attitude...you determine how you use your 24 hours in the day...you decide whether to take action or to settle. So choice(s) will you make to be the best version of yourself in this short life we live? #mondaymood #perspective

caption:
15 months postpartum vs. 3 months.
Then: 70 lbs (second slide)
Today: 105 lbs (first slide)

And the third photo in this series was from my first stroller run, exactly one year ago. It was a 2 mile run, and I felt like I was dying the entire time. My SI joint also hurt post-run, and this run was the catalyst for putting a firm halt to any further running and dedicating myself to strength.

Yesterday I ran a 12 miles with a workout in the middle, painfree, and feel the best Iâ€˜ve felt in years. But it took MONTHS of 10-30 minute runs, hill strides, and soooo much patience.

Not shown in between these photos: Tears. Lows. Highs. Feeling discouraged. Realizing that Iâ€™m stronger than I thought. Not believing Iâ€™d ever run fast again. Going to the gym super late, after the baby was sleeping. Finding a new purpose to training. PRing, both in running and lifting.

Instagram is filled with flashy photos, videos, and journies that seem incredible on the surface. Donâ€™t forget thereâ€™s a lot behind the scenes that is never shown or talked about here. For me, postpartum fitness has been about finding my own strength and learning how to be the best mom I can be to my sweet boy. Everyone has their own story and their own goals; just never forget to stay true to who YOU are.

caption:
FEELINGS donâ€™t matter.ğŸ’€ğŸ‘ğŸ»
I know youâ€™re thinking what?!? Feelings are everything!!! Let me clarify, you matter, but your feelings are often a shitty measurement for happiness and living the life you desire to live. Just because you feel a certain way doesnâ€™t mean that it is reality. Just because you love someone, doesnâ€™t mean they love you back. Just because youâ€™re anxious about work, doesnâ€™t mean you are doomed to fail. What WILL CAUSE you to FAIL is relying on your feelings as a whole. Guess what? I donâ€™t feel like working out 8/10 times. But I do. I donâ€™t feel like reading. But I do. I donâ€™t feel like eating healthy, but I do most of the time. I donâ€™t feel like talking on the phone, but for whoever Iâ€™m calling it does more for them than it does for me. I donâ€™t feel like working. But I do. I donâ€™t feel like keeping my mouth shut to keep the peace, but I have. When you realize that YOU dictate how your day goes, based on how you respond to it and WHAT you do, not how you FEEL you will be so empowered. Donâ€™t get stuck in feelings. Donâ€™t get stuck in anxiety. Donâ€™t get stuck in sadness and let it lead you to a road of nothing but pain and turmoil. You have to make a decision EVERYDAY to do the work regardless of how you feel. Loving someone is a decision. Loving yourself is a decision. Doing the work regardless is a decision. Sitting sad and empty because you decided to feel like crap, is a decision. Iâ€™m deciding to feel good based on my future and the things I have to be grateful for RIGHT NOW. Sure, sad emotions and down times happen, but Iâ€™m not a victim and I donâ€™t stay knocked down. I make a decision to get up every day and focus on the things that FEEL good. Donâ€™t let your feelings lie to you. Donâ€™t let them keep you down. You have a million reasons and excuses you can use to feel like crap, and you have a million reasons to feel amazing and excited for life. Itâ€™s UP TO YOU. Start living based on your decisions and not getting stuck in a feeling. Your life will drastically transform when you do. ğŸ’¯

caption: â—¼ï¸Feeling stuck? Fall in love with learning. Anytime I feel as though Iâ€™m stalling, I dive into YouTube videos, books, podcasts, whatever I can get my hands on. Iâ€™ve been watching videos and learning online from people for years doing the very thing Iâ€™m working on to do. You donâ€™t need to reinvent the wheel. You can REFINE it though. caption: #TBT at Cafe GratitudeğŸ’šIâ€™ve been emotional eating randomly. It doesnâ€™t mean over eating, just in ways that arenâ€™t healthy in general. So Iâ€™m currently on a juice cleanse to reset. Guess what - I struggle too! And if you feel like you canâ€™t live without something, try giving it up a week and see how you feel. I use stevia like itâ€™s going to become extinct. The problem with sweeteners, even if they say low glycemic index (doesnâ€™t spike blood sugars) they still mess with your body and can cause weight gain if you use them too much. When you eat something sweet your body is waiting on sugar to digest. When it doesnâ€™t get it, even if it claims it doesnâ€™t -it can mess with blood sugar levels and spike cravings. I realized I was hardly eating but always hungry, and eating more â€œhealthy junk foodâ€ than ever. So learn to listen to your body. Give up caffeine, alcohol, sugar, sweeteners, for a short time and see how it resets your taste, energy and mind. This is not fun for me. I thrive on coffee and stevia. Stevia is great, when in pure form. But donâ€™t get it mixed with dextrose, or sugar, on accident like I did. (I may as well be eating cake all day ğŸ¤¦ğŸ»â€â™€ï¸). And too much of it can affect your hormones. Do you have something that isnâ€™t necessarily bad but you may be over eating it? Do a literal gut check. If youâ€™re tired, bloated, and hungry all the time itâ€™s a sign something is off. Iâ€™ll add the organic version back in moderation later when I feel great again. Until then celery juice and matcha tea takes its place. Have a good day friends! ğŸâ˜ºï¸

caption:

Whatâ€™s on your plate over the next week? Mine involves doing some shoots for various clients, school assignments, and other work stuff!

Just ask yourself the question: what is my ultimate goal? Are the tasks Iâ€™m filling my days with helping me get there? 

Your ultimate goal could be to own your own business. To have your own family. To work in a field youâ€™re passionate about. Whatever it is, donâ€™t lose sight of that long-term goal. 

With that in mind, donâ€™t get too caught  up over the little things. You donâ€™t have to take you every opportunity youâ€™re presented with. Itâ€™s okay to pass up events, to have a messy house every now and then, to fail an exam. Chances are those will have little effect in the long run :)

caption:
Who do you love in your life who might be pretty â€œdifferentâ€ from you?

When we started dating, we realized that we are...very different! 

I laugh at it now. For a moment though, I let it psych me out. â€œWill we have similar interests? Will we want the same things? What about our careers?â€ I thought. 

Iâ€™m a student, very creative and ambitious. I sing and dance in public for fun. He works full time in ministry (for @thefcateam), is a morning bird, and is a chill, sweet, lowkey guy. I love fashion, he is a sports man through and through! 

However, what became very apparent is that our different hobbies and lifestyles werenâ€™t stumbling blocks. Our differences compliment each otherâ€™s. If we were copies of each other, we would have the same weak spots and strengths! 

If we had passed each other up on account of being â€œtoo differentâ€ we would have been MAJORLY missing out! 

What matters for us is that we both have the same desireâ€”to chase after the Lord. Weâ€™re able to do that together which is such a blessing! 

Willis has amazing character that I truly admire. He is kind, extremely generous, intentional with his relationships and silly. The Lord only makes those qualities stronger and better as he grows with God!

Character > Commonalities â¤ï¸
